# Walkthrough: Project Analysis of WAGW

I have completed the analysis of the **WhatsApp Gateway Multi-Device (WAGW)** project. Below is a summary of the work performed.

## Work Performed
- **Initial Exploration**: Scanned the project directory and identified it as a Node.js/Express application.
- **Tech Stack Identification**: Identified key libraries like `@whiskeysockets/baileys`, `sqlite3`, `socket.io`, and `swagger`.
- **Deep Dive Analysis**: 
  - Analyzed [connection.js](file:///home/liloneda/Apps%20Realm/wagw/connection.js) for session management and multi-device support.
  - Analyzed [message.js](file:///home/liloneda/Apps%20Realm/wagw/message.js) for single and bulk blast messaging logic.
  - Analyzed [database.js](file:///home/liloneda/Apps%20Realm/wagw/database.js) for logging and security.
- **Documentation Review**: Checked [README.md](file:///home/liloneda/Apps%20Realm/wagw/README.md) and [swagger.js](file:///home/liloneda/Apps%20Realm/wagw/swagger.js) for API specifications.

## Key Findings
- The project is well-architected for its purpose, supporting multi-device rotation and randomized messaging to avoid spam detection.
- It uses SQLite for lightweight data persistence and has built-in security via API keys.
- It is container-ready with a Dockerfile.

